              <span id="reviewTextContainer2469619443" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7095643000720152374">Betrayal in Blue is a fictional thriller written by Mark M. Bello. It begins by introducing us to the Dearborn Police Department (PD) that has just managed to retrieve a piece of information on the dark web about the possible plotting of a terror mission directed at Dearborn, its cops, and Muslims. <br/><br/>Jack Dylan is a veteran of the Dearborn PD, and his team’s key members include Andy Toller―forensic criminologist, Noah Thompson―cybercrime expert, and Shaheed Ali―Muslim affairs expert. The team is m</span>
  <span id="freeText7095643000720152374" style="display:none">Betrayal in Blue is a fictional thriller written by Mark M. Bello. It begins by introducing us to the Dearborn Police Department (PD) that has just managed to retrieve a piece of information on the dark web about the possible plotting of a terror mission directed at Dearborn, its cops, and Muslims. <br /><br />Jack Dylan is a veteran of the Dearborn PD, and his team’s key members include Andy Toller―forensic criminologist, Noah Thompson―cybercrime expert, and Shaheed Ali―Muslim affairs expert. The team is more like a friendship forged over many years.<br /><br />Since I hadn’t read the last two instalments in the series, it took me a while to get into this story. For the first few chapters, you are introduced to a number of different characters who seem to have mostly been part of the previous books in the series. <br /><br />The story takes place in a time where racism is still quite alive and violence and attacks against minorities are a prominent feature of the society. There is also a lot of legal drama in the story, which―to me―was the highlight of the book. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7095643000720152374" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

