    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2686746665" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2686746665" />
    <a title="Terrafied" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32592656-terrafied"><img alt="Terrafied" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1505592270p2/32592656.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2686746665?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Terrafied" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Terrafied" href="/user/show/32592656-terrafied">Terrafied</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2686746665" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16254315666608201601"><br/>Betrayal in Blue was written by Mark M. Bello and recently released on Sept 21, 2018. It is the third book in a series about Jack Dylan a captain in the Dearborn, Michigan police department. He continues his fight with a new white supremacist group bent on exacting revenge of Benjamin Blaine’s (A white supremacist leader from the earlier book Betrayal of Justice) capture. The Free America Party wants to use sarin gas to attack a Muslim church in Dearborn and take down the Dearborn police departm</span>
  <span id="freeText16254315666608201601" style="display:none"><br />Betrayal in Blue was written by Mark M. Bello and recently released on Sept 21, 2018. It is the third book in a series about Jack Dylan a captain in the Dearborn, Michigan police department. He continues his fight with a new white supremacist group bent on exacting revenge of Benjamin Blaine’s (A white supremacist leader from the earlier book Betrayal of Justice) capture. The Free America Party wants to use sarin gas to attack a Muslim church in Dearborn and take down the Dearborn police department. From there the unexpected begins! I have rated this book two out of four stars. I really loved the surprise elements in the book, the plot points and the in-depth knowledge of weapons and courtroom proceedings while I struggled with the character building, descriptions of settings and the motives of certain characters which impacted my overall rating of the book.<br /><br />I truly enjoy my crime dramas which made this book an easy read. It moved along at a good pace. Just when I was ready for the next plot point in the book it delivered. I loved not knowing what to expect, while being surprised and wondering how these new developments will change my expectations of the ending of the story. My favorite part in the book is when Jack Dylan on his own time goes after Bart Breitner the leader of the Free America Party to the small town of Manistee, Michigan. Next thing you know instead of arresting Bart Breitner... I can’t tell tell you because it would be a spoiler.<br /><br />Bello clearly has done his research into the technical parts of the story. It was obvious he had in-depth knowledge about sarin gas, weapons, tactical police teams. Bello was a lawyer before he became an author and it really showed in Zachary Blake’s character as the defense attorney for Jack Dylan. In fact Zachary Blake ended up being my favorite character because it was clear Bello loved to write about him. Zack was smart, thoughtful, witty and clearly was a great attorney. <br /><br />While all these parts were fun and enjoyable, I really struggled with the character building, descriptions of people and settings. There was a lot of telling and not showing in this book such as I never really knew what Jack Dylan looks like other than “distinguished looking middle-aged man who was graying at the temples.” pg. 7 What is his ethnicity? How tall is he? What is the color of his eyes? I also don’t know anything about Jack. Was he born in Dearborn Michigan? Why did he become a cop? Does he have any family? Was he married? Does he have any kids? Why did he defy explicit orders to track down Breitner knowing he could lose his career over it? There wasn’t enough description or background to really show why someone as smart as Jack decided it was worth it to risk it all.<br /><br />I really wanted to give this book three out of four stars but I couldn’t. There were too many holes and gaps in the story. When Jack get bailed out of jail in one scene where does he stay? What is he thinking? A man of action won’t be happy with staying cooped up but there was nothing written at all while his lawyer was building his defense. Also, Bart Bretiner doesn’t seem to have any motive to being a white supremacist. The level of planning Bart Bretiner went to bomb the Muslim church he couldn’t have just been an average racist.There was no background on his life that led him on this path. It made his character unbelievable.<br /><br />The character building and descriptions are what really makes me fall in love with stories. I need texture, color, layers. I want the towns that Jack was in to have their own personality. I wanted to see the kind of culture and society of the people they held within their walls. It helps give motives to the people in the story. It makes the characters more alive. I didn’t find it in this book at all and I think it is why I struggled with the linchpin of the story, which I can’t tell you about because I don’t want to give any spoilers.<br /><br />Overall, I had to rate this book two out of four stars for these reasons. It doesn’t mean I didn’t like the story. If a reader is looking for a book that is all about action, then I recommend it! It is perfect for reading while stuck in a layover at an airport or a fun summer camping read or snuggled up on the couch during a rainy day.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16254315666608201601" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

